            "heading": "Drain Lines and Grease Traps",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "text_86wez9": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><br/>Grease and fats naturally float on water, causing them to stick and solidify along the walls and ceilings of your drain lines. Meanwhile, sugars and starches sink and accumulate at the bottom, eventually leading to stubborn clogs and slow drainage. Over time, this organic buildup results in unpleasant odors, provides an ideal breeding ground for drain flies, and forces grease traps or interceptors to require constant, costly cleaning.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        },
